  footnotes: []
english:
  title: Responding to Minister Lee's Rhyme at Bu-an
  author: Seo Geo-jeong
  language: eng
  text: |-
    Ten years our letters crossed through east and west,
    and now atop this tower, I rejoice to stand with you.
    Rain voices linger long upon the banana leaves,
    while spring's hue settles deep within the peony grove.
    My life already surrendered in wine-cups,
    my years spent idle at the crossroads of wandering.
    Yet drunk, I still recall that southern dream—
    a thousand lotus blooms burning crimson for ten leagues.
  footnotes:
  - key: ''
    value: Minister Lee (李相國) likely refers to Lee served in a high ministerial position at court, a contemporary or acquaintance of the poet.
  - key: ''
    value: The 'southern dream' evokes memories of travel or longing for distant places, a common motif in classical Chinese and Korean poetry.
  - key: ''
    value: The final image of lotus flowers spanning ten leagues suggests a landscape of overwhelming beauty, emphasizing both the richness of memory and the transience of experience.
